<ElementPointercancel_event>
<summary>
The <strong><c>pointercancel</c></strong> event is fired when the browser determines that there are unlikely to be any more pointer events, or if after the <see cref="Element/pointerdown_event"/> event is fired, the pointer is then used to manipulate the viewport by panning, zooming, or scrolling.
</summary>
<remarks>
<para>Some examples of situations that will trigger a <c>pointercancel</c> event:</para><blockquote class="NOTE"><h5>NOTE</h5><para><strong>Note:</strong> After the <c>pointercancel</c> event is fired, the browser will also send <see cref="Element/pointerout_event"/> followed by <see cref="Element/pointerleave_event"/>.</para></blockquote>
